          "body": "Deuteronomy 23:1 excluded the man wounded in his private parts from the assembly of the LORD. Deuteronomy 23:3 excluded the Ammonite and Moabite to the tenth generation. Isaiah 56 does not argue with Deuteronomy; it announces that the eschatological salvation now approaching supersedes the provisional boundaries of the Mosaic economy. The eunuch's self-description — 'I am a dry tree' — is one of the Bible's most poignant images of double desolation: excluded from the community and unable to produce heirs. God's response is a *yad* (memorial, literally 'hand' — a monument) and a *shem* (name) within His very house, better than sons and daughters (56:5). The foreigner who joins himself (*lavah*, attaches, cleaves — the same root as Levi and Ruth 1:14) to minister and to love the LORD's name is brought to the holy mountain and made joyful (56:7). The repeated criteria in both oracles are identical: keep the Sabbath, hold fast the covenant, choose what pleases God. Ethnicity and physical condition are not the deciding factors; covenantal faithfulness is. Peter Davids's observation about James's hermeneutic of reversal applies here too — God consistently inverts the honor economy of the ancient world."
