          "title": "A house of prayer for all peoples — the chapter's center of gravity (56:7)",
          "body": "The phrase 'My house shall be called a house of prayer for all the peoples' (*kol-ha'ammim*, 56:7) is the chapter's theological summit and the most explicitly quoted verse in the NT from this chapter. Jesus cites it in all three Synoptic accounts of the temple cleansing (Matthew 21:13; Mark 11:17; Luke 19:46). His citation is precise: the court of the Gentiles — the one precinct within the temple precincts reserved for non-Israelite worshippers, the very space promised to the foreigner in Isaiah 56:6-7 — had been turned into a commercial marketplace. Jesus drives out the traders and cites Isaiah 56:7 as the stated purpose of that space. The chapter's eschatological promise becomes the exegetical basis for a prophetic act. The phrase 'for all peoples' (*kol-ha'ammim*) is not a vague aspiration; it is a programmatic statement about the temple's design — which the Herodian expansion had honored architecturally and the money-changers had violated practically. Calvin notes that the passage shows that 'God has never had a different design than that all nations should be gathered into one body' (Commentary on Isaiah, ad loc.)."
